The plosive {{IPA|/p/}} is realized as {{IPA|[p]}} in the syllable onset but as {{IPA|[pʔᵐ]}} (which contrasts with the simple nasal phoneme {{IPA|/m/}}) in the coda. Similarly, {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/k/}} are realized as {{IPA|[tʔⁿ]}} and {{IPA|[ʔ<sup>ɤ</sup>]}} (i.e., as a [[glottal stop]] with a vocalic release), respectively, in the syllable coda.<ref name="Katharina Haude 2006"/> In vowel-initial words and between adjacent vowels, an epenthetic glottal stop appears.

The phonemes {{IPA|/f/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}} are only present in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] loanwords.

==Morphology==
In Movima, [[compound (linguistics)|compound]]ing and [[incorporation (linguistics)|incorporation]] are productive [[derivational morphology|derivational]] processes. [[Reduplication]] and [[affix]]ation, including some processes (such as the [[irrealis]] marker ''(k)a''') that resemble [[infix]]ation, are also common. Typical examples of [[inflection]], such as [[grammatical number|number]], [[grammatical case|case]], [[grammatical tense|tense]], [[grammatical mood|mood]], and [[grammatical aspect|aspect]], are not obligatorily marked in Movima.<ref name="Katharina Haude 2006"/> Many derivational processes can be applied to a single Movima word. The same morpheme may appear multiple times in one word this way, for instance, ''tikoy-na-poj-na'' "I make X kill Y."

